American Indian Area code. The U.S. Census Bureau uses codes in the InterNational Committee for Information Technology Standards (INCITS) 446-2008 standard to identify American Indian areas. This standard “Applies to selected named physical and cultural geographic features, geographic areas, and locational entities, except roads and highways, that are generally recognizable and locatable by name (i.e., have achieved some landmark status) and are of interest to any level of government and to the public for any purpose that would lead to the representation of the feature in printed or electronic maps and/or geographic information systems".
For more information:
https://www.census.gov/library/reference/code-lists/ansi.html; description of INCITS 446-2008 standard: https://standards.incits.org/apps/group_public/project/details.php?project_id=1675, a PDF of which can be purchased at https://webstore.ansi.org/Standards/INCITS/ANSIINCITS4462008; however, for a list of all AIA codes that US Census uses, see https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/reference/codes/AIAlist.txt

dataIdInfo.idPurp: Indian Territory Boundaries in New York State.
dataIdInfo.idAbs:
Published: October 2021

A vector polygon GIS file of all Indian Territory boundaries in New York State. The file was originally a compilation of U.S. Geological Survey 1:100,000-scale digital vector files and NYS Department of Transportation 1:24,000-scale and 1:75,000-scale digital vector files. Boundaries were revised to 1:24,000-scale positional accuracy. Currently, boundary changes are made as needed based on authoritative sources.
